{
  "text": "Whether estrogens, androgens, and/or progesterone and its metabolites are synthesized in the CNS/PNS depends upon many factors including timing during development, expression of metabolism enzymes, and their substrates in particular tissues (brain regions), cell types (i.e. neurons vs. glia), and/or cellular regions (cell bodies, fibers, etc.). Neurosteroids are formed from biosynthesis of cholesterol by P450 and non-P450 enzymes (17b-HSD, aromatase, 3a-HSD, 5a-reductase). Gene expression of P450c17, is developmentally Diagram 1 Sources of 3a,5a-THP in the CNS include de novo biosynthesis in glial cells and metabolism of peripheral or central P. S146 C.A. Frye regulated with early expression being different from that observed in the mature brain [CITATION_1] . This implies that certain metabolites may play key roles that are relegated throughout development without continuous expression in adulthood. Further, there are developmental differences in the substrates that two 3a-HSDs in human fetal brain utilize, with one using DHP and another using DHT (reviewed in [CITATION_2] . Conservation in the localization of steroidogenic enzymes, which are involved in synthesizing neurosteroids, to specific brain regions within a variety of species, indicates that their function may be similar throughout evolution. Some investigations have attempted to colocalize steroidogenic enzymes in whole brain, neuronal, and/or glial cell cultures. Indeed, some steroidogenic enzymes are expressed only in neurons, or only in glia (type 1 astrocytes, Schwann cells), while other enzymes are expressed in both cell types [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . Investigations are still needed to elucidate how specific brain regions synthesize or metabolize steroids, which are essential to reveal the function of neurosteroids. Ascertaining the relative concentrations of peripheral versus central levels of 3a,5a-THP is of great interest to understanding the functional significance of neurosteroids.",
